metadata.name: Vast Difference #19
metadata.description:
This piece explores the dynamic creation of vascular cages around generative geometries. Particles are projected at a generative form, stopping when contact is made with any of the form's faces. A curve is then generated through the particles, based on the order of particle-face collision. Finally, custom tube geometry is extruded along the curve path, determining the final cage mesh. 

Interactivity: 
Panning, rotating, zooming and toggling both the internal form and particle nodes on/off.

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
o, n: hide | show particle nodes
i, v: hide | show internal form
p: screen capture

Notes:
Some renders produce noticeable delays, including possible browser alerts/warnings. This is expected behavior.
Please post your favorite 'Vast Difference' screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #992
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: DisOrder #235
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 84 · 56 · 38 · 26 · 18  every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All that is, starts with Order.

Order attempts to evade entropy by following its own intrinsic patterns. Then, inevitably, there is change: an anomaly, a nudge that turns into a catalyst for widespread change.The momentum cannot be stopped.

Brief cycles build upon themselves, iterating and breaking into something new with each turn. Now, looking back, the accumulation of small divergences look like a leap, with trails of evolutionary decline casting tall shadows on the patterns that bore them.

The beauty of what this entropy creates, rises beyond chaos. It represents the past, and signals the future, and suddenly looks like a wild take on Order itself – the true DisOrder of life.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////
